# UK Compliance Accordion + T&Cs Generator — Developer Documentation

**Scope:** Physical merchants only. Extracted from the `playe` project for re-use on your existing platform.

This package contains three React components plus a type contract:

| File | Purpose |
|---|---|
| `ComplianceSection.tsx` | The "UK Compliance" accordion item — FER, age gate, geo, marketing opt-in, PECR & EXIF acks. |
| `TermsBuilder.tsx`      | Guided T&Cs generator + free-form fallback textarea. Outputs CAP §8-compliant prose. |
| `PreLaunchChecklist.tsx`| Read-only validation card (physical-only variant). Gate your Publish button on `allPassed`. |
| `types.ts`              | Minimum campaign-state shape the three components depend on. |

All three components are pure React + shadcn/ui (`accordion`, `button`, `badge`, `card`, `input`, `label`, `select`, `switch`, `textarea`) + `lucide-react` icons + `date-fns` (for `TermsBuilder` only). No other runtime dependencies.

---

## 1. How to wire it up

The components read and write state via a `useWizard()` hook that exposes:

```ts
{
  campaignData: CampaignComplianceData,        // see types.ts
  updateCampaignData: (patch: Partial<…>) => void,
  merchantType: "physical" | "cpg" | "ecommerce" | null,
}
```

Two integration options:

**Option A — add these fields to your existing campaign-draft model.** Expose a hook with the same name and shape. Hard-code `merchantType: "physical"` if your platform only ever serves physical merchants.

**Option B — wrap a small dedicated context** around the compliance state and keep it separate from the rest of your form. Simplest if you don't want to touch your existing model.

Either way, the three components don't care how state is persisted — they only call `updateCampaignData()` with field-level patches.

### Placement in the form

```
Step "Game Logic"           Step "Timing & Visibility"
─────────────────           ──────────────────────────
<Accordion>                 <Accordion>                  
  ...                         <AccordionItem value="terms">
  <ComplianceSection />         <AccordionTrigger>Terms & Conditions</AccordionTrigger>
</Accordion>                    <AccordionContent>
                                  <TermsBuilder />
                                </AccordionContent>
                              </AccordionItem>
                            </Accordion>
                            <PreLaunchChecklist />
```

`ComplianceSection` IS the `<AccordionItem>` — it must be a direct child of `<Accordion type="single" collapsible>`. `TermsBuilder` is content you wrap in your own accordion item.

---

## 2. The logic — why each control exists

### 2.1 Free Entry Route (FER)

**Trigger:** `campaignStyle === "Fixed-Pool"` only.

**Why:** Under the UK **Gambling Act 2005**, a promotion is an illegal lottery if three elements coincide — (1) payment to enter, (2) prize, (3) outcome decided by chance. A "Free Entry Route" of equal merit removes element (1) and converts the promotion to a lawful prize draw.

| Campaign style    | Needs FER? | Why |
|-------------------|------------|-----|
| Fixed-Pool        | **Yes**    | Chance-based draw from a finite pool. |
| Single Win        | No         | Skill-based — winner judged on merit. |
| Leaderboard       | No         | Skill-based — ranked by score. |
| Reward for All    | No         | Guaranteed gift-with-purchase, not a draw. |

The accordion hides the entire FER block when not legally required, so merchants running skill or guaranteed-reward campaigns aren't asked irrelevant questions. The `PreLaunchChecklist` also conditionally adds an FER check only for Fixed-Pool.

FER methods supported: **postal**, **free web form**, **free SMS shortcode**, **skill question** (the skill option itself satisfies the "no chance" criterion, so no separate free address is needed).

### 2.2 Age gate

Default `18+`. CAP guidance: use 18+ whenever the prize is alcohol, gambling-adjacent, or high-value. Persisted as `ageGate` and printed in §2 of the generated T&Cs.

### 2.3 Geographic eligibility

Default `uk`. Provide `uk-ex-ni` because **Northern Ireland has separate lottery rules** under the Betting, Gaming, Lotteries and Amusements (NI) Order 1985 — excluding NI is the safe default when unsure. `eea` and `global` are available for international prize draws (note: those bring further jurisdictional rules out of scope here).

### 2.4 Marketing opt-in (unbundled)

Under **UK GDPR Art. 7** and **PECR reg. 22**, marketing consent must be:
- **Specific** to marketing (not bundled with "I accept the T&Cs"),
- **Freely given** (not a condition of entry),
- **Opt-in** (pre-ticked boxes are invalid — *Planet49* CJEU C-673/17).

This toggle records that the merchant has surfaced a separate, optional marketing tick on their entry form. The checklist flags it red if missing.

### 2.5 PECR consent for device fingerprinting

Only shown when `deviceFingerprinting === true`. **PECR reg. 6** (the "cookie rule") covers any storage of or access to information on the user's device that isn't strictly necessary for the requested service. Device fingerprinting falls inside that — informed consent is required *before* the fingerprint is computed, not after.

### 2.6 EXIF / location data lawful basis (physical-merchant feature)

Only shown when `exifScan === true`. Physical merchants commonly accept "photo of receipt" as proof of purchase. JPEGs from phone cameras embed EXIF GPS coordinates — under UK GDPR these are **location data** (Art. 4(1)) and need a stated lawful basis in the privacy notice. Toggle records merchant acknowledgement.

---

## 3. The T&Cs generator

`TermsBuilder.generateTerms()` writes a 10-clause body to `campaignData.termsAndConditions`. The merchant can then edit it in the textarea or toggle the builder off and start from scratch.

### Clauses produced

1. **PROMOTER** — `promoterName`, `promoterAddress` (CAP §8.17 mandatory)
2. **ELIGIBILITY** — `whoCanEnter`, `ageGate`, `geoRestriction`
3. **PROMOTION PERIOD** — **switches on `merchantType`** (see §3.1 below)
4. **HOW TO ENTER** — paid route + (if Fixed-Pool) the configured FER
   - **4a. SIGNIFICANT CONDITIONS** — auto-appended when `minimumSpend > 0` or style is "Reward for All". Required by CAP §8.17 to be stated up-front.
5. **PRIZE** — quantity, total value, reward type
6. **WINNER SELECTION & NOTIFICATION** — text switches on `campaignStyle`; uses `winnerNotificationDays` (default 7) and `prizeDeliveryDays` (default 28)
7. **PRIZE SUBSTITUTION** — based on `prizeSubstitutionAllowed`
8. **WINNER PUBLICATION** — `full` / `anonymised` / `on-request`
9. **DATA PROTECTION** — free text, default mentions UK GDPR
10. **GOVERNING LAW** — default "England & Wales"

### 3.1 Physical-merchant closing clause (CRITICAL — don't lose this)

Physical-merchant pools close on **participant-pool exhaustion**, not calendar end. The generator emits:

> This promotion closes when the finite pool of participant numbers has been fully activated. A long-stop date of `<endDate>` applies; any participant numbers not activated by that date are void. A "campaign closed" notice will be published within 24 hours of pool exhaustion.

This is an **event-based terminus** under **CAP §8.17.1(b)** — permissible provided a long-stop date is published. Non-physical merchants get the calendar-close clause instead.

If `merchantType !== "physical"` in your platform you can simplify by hard-coding `isPhysical = true` inside `generateTerms()`, but keep the long-stop sentence — it's what makes the event-based terminus compliant.

### 3.2 Significant conditions

CAP §8.17 requires "significant conditions" (anything that materially affects the entrant's decision to participate) to be stated **before** entry — not buried in clause 14 of the T&Cs. The generator currently auto-flags:

- **Minimum qualifying spend** (when `minimumSpend > 0`)
- **Reward-for-All** disclosure (because entrants might otherwise expect a draw)

Add new auto-flags by pushing onto the `significantConditions[]` array in `generateTerms()`.

---

## 4. The pre-launch checklist

`PreLaunchChecklist` is a read-only validation summary. It returns a badge with `X / N passed` and lists each failure with a remediation hint. Hide your Publish button (or show a warning modal) when `passedCount < items.length`.

Physical-merchant checks included:

- FER configured *(only when Fixed-Pool)*
- Minimum-spend disclosure present in T&Cs *(only when min spend > 0)* — naive substring check on the T&C body for "minimum" + "spend"/"qualifying"
- Age gate set
- Promoter legal name & address present
- T&C body length > 100 chars
- Marketing opt-in surfaced
- PECR ack when fingerprinting on
- Location-data ack when EXIF scan on
- Winner notification window set
- Prize delivery SLA ≤ 30 days

CPG and Ecommerce branches from the original codebase have been **stripped** in this physical-only build.

---

## 5. Legal references (quick index)

| Reference                | What it covers                                            |
|--------------------------|------------------------------------------------------------|
| Gambling Act 2005, s.14, sch.2 | Defines lottery vs prize competition; FER carve-out. |
| CAP Code §8 (Sales Promotions) | Significant conditions, mandatory T&C fields, SLAs.  |
| CAP §8.17                | Mandatory disclosures including promoter identity, closing date/terminus, significant conditions. |
| CAP §8.17.1(b)           | Permits event-based closing terminus (used by physical pools). |
| UK GDPR Art. 6 + 7       | Lawful basis + consent quality. |
| UK GDPR Art. 4(1)        | Location data definition. |
| PECR reg. 6              | Consent for non-essential device storage/access (covers fingerprinting). |
| PECR reg. 22             | Consent for electronic marketing. |
| CJEU C-673/17 (Planet49) | Pre-ticked consent boxes are invalid. |
| Betting, Gaming, Lotteries and Amusements (NI) Order 1985 | Separate NI lottery regime — reason for `uk-ex-ni` option. |

This package codifies the controls those rules require. It is **not legal advice** — final T&C text should be reviewed by qualified counsel before each campaign.

---

## 6. Field cross-reference

If your existing platform already has some of these fields under different names, here is the full set the components read/write (see `types.ts` for the canonical TypeScript):

`campaignStyle`, `merchantType`, `deviceFingerprinting`, `exifScan`, `lineItemMatch`, `sku`, `freeEntryRoute`, `freeEntryDetails`, `ageGate`, `geoRestriction`, `marketingOptInOffered`, `pecrAcknowledged`, `locationDataAcknowledged`, `termsBuilderEnabled`, `promoterName`, `promoterAddress`, `whoCanEnter`, `governingLaw`, `dataProtectionStatement`, `termsAndConditions`, `minimumSpend`, `prizeQuantity`, `prizeValue`, `rewardType`, `winnerNotificationDays`, `prizeDeliveryDays`, `winnerPublication`, `prizeSubstitutionAllowed`, `judgeName`, `judgeRole`, `endDate`.

Map them to your existing schema in your hook/adapter — the components are dumb consumers of the contract.
